    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Papillary Muscle Rupture", content: "Papillary muscle rupture is a catastrophic mechanical complication of acute myocardial infarction, occurring 2-7 days post-MI when ischemic necrosis weakens the papillary muscle to the point of partial or complete rupture. The posteromedial papillary muscle is affected five times more frequently than the anterolateral because it has a single blood supply (posterior descending artery), whereas the anterolateral papillary muscle has dual blood supply (LAD and circumflex arteries). Complete rupture causes sudden, severe mitral regurgitation with massive left atrial volume overload, elevated left atrial pressure transmitted to the pulmonary veins (causing flash pulmonary edema), and acute cardiogenic shock. The patient presents with sudden-onset severe dyspnea, a new harsh holosystolic murmur (though the murmur may be soft or absent due to equalization of left atrial and ventricular pressures), and rapidly progressive hemodynamic collapse. The RN recognizes sudden clinical deterioration in a post-MI patient (new murmur, acute pulmonary edema, hypotension), positions in high Fowler's, administers oxygen, initiates hemodynamic monitoring, manages afterload reduction (nitroprusside if blood pressure permits) to reduce regurgitant volume, assists with intra-aortic balloon pump placement, and prepares for emergent cardiac surgery (mitral valve repair or replacement) as the definitive treatment." },
